events.description: The Catholicon, written in 1464 by Jehan Lagadeuc in Tréguier, is published; this is the first Breton dictionary as well as the first French dictionary.

events.description: Second Battle of Panipat: Fighting begins between the forces of Hem Chandra Vikramaditya, the Hindu king at Delhi and the forces of the Muslim emperor Akbar.

events.description: Prince William III of Orange lands with a Dutch fleet at Brixham to challenge the rule of King James II of England (James VII of Scotland).
events.html: • 1688 – Prince William III of Orange lands with a Dutch fleet at Brixham to challenge the rule of King James II of England (James VII of Scotland).[2]

events.description: Seven Years' War: Frederick the Great defeats the allied armies of France and the Holy Roman Empire at the Battle of Rossbach.
events.html: • 1757 – Seven Years' War: Frederick the Great defeats the allied armies of France and the Holy Roman Empire at the Battle of Rossbach.

events.description: The Treaty of Fort Stanwix is signed, the purpose of which is to adjust the boundary line between Indian lands and white settlements set forth in the Royal Proclamation of 1763 in the Thirteen Colonies.
events.html: • 1768 – The Treaty of Fort Stanwix is signed, the purpose of which is to adjust the boundary line between Indian lands and white settlements set forth in the Royal Proclamation of 1763 in the Thirteen Colonies.

events.description: French-American forces under Colonel LaBalme are defeated by Miami Chief Little Turtle.
events.html: • 1780 – French-American forces under Colonel LaBalme are defeated by Miami Chief Little Turtle.

events.description: Salvadoran priest José Matías Delgado rings the bells of La Merced church in San Salvador, calling for insurrection and launching the 1811 Independence Movement.
events.html: • 1811 – Salvadoran priest José Matías Delgado rings the bells of La Merced church in San Salvador, calling for insurrection and launching the 1811 Independence Movement.

events.description: Greek War of Independence: The French Morea expedition to recapture Morea (now the Peloponnese) ends when the last Ottoman forces depart the peninsula.
events.html: • 1828 – Greek War of Independence: The French Morea expedition to recapture Morea (now the Peloponnese) ends when the last Ottoman forces depart the peninsula.

events.description: Founding of the Free University of Brussels by Pierre-Théodore Verhaegen.
events.html: • 1834 – Founding of the Free University of Brussels by Pierre-Théodore Verhaegen.[3]

events.description: American Civil War: Abraham Lincoln removes George B. McClellan as commander of the Army of the Potomac.
events.html: • 1862 – American Civil War: Abraham Lincoln removes George B. McClellan as commander of the Army of the Potomac.

events.description: American Indian Wars: In Minnesota, 303 Dakota warriors are found guilty of rape and murder of whites and are sentenced to death. Thirty-eight are ultimately hanged and the others reprieved.
events.html: • 1862 – American Indian Wars: In Minnesota, 303 Dakota warriors are found guilty of rape and murder of whites and are sentenced to death. Thirty-eight are ultimately hanged and the others reprieved.

events.description: Women's suffrage in the United States: In defiance of the law, suffragist Susan B. Anthony votes for the first time, and is later fined $100.
events.html: • 1872 – Women's suffrage in the United States: In defiance of the law, suffragist Susan B. Anthony votes for the first time, and is later fined $100.

events.description: In New Zealand, 1600 armed volunteers and constabulary field forces led by Minister of Native Affairs John Bryce march on the pacifist Māori settlement at Parihaka, evicting upwards of 2000 residents, and destroying the settlement in the context of the New Zealand land confiscations.
events.html: • 1881 – In New Zealand, 1600 armed volunteers and constabulary field forces led by Minister of Native Affairs John Bryce march on the pacifist Māori settlement at Parihaka, evicting upwards of 2000 residents, and destroying the settlement in the context of the New Zealand land confiscations.[4]

events.description: George B. Selden is granted the first U.S. patent for an automobile.
events.html: • 1895 – George B. Selden is granted the first U.S. patent for an automobile.

events.description: Negrese nationalists revolt against Spanish rule and establish the short-lived Republic of Negros.
events.html: • 1898 – Negrese nationalists revolt against Spanish rule and establish the short-lived Republic of Negros.

events.description: After declaring war on the Ottoman Empire on September 29, 1911, Italy annexes Tripoli and Cyrenaica.
events.html: • 1911 – After declaring war on the Ottoman Empire on September 29, 1911, Italy annexes Tripoli and Cyrenaica.

events.description: Woodrow Wilson is elected the 28th President of the United States, defeating incumbent William Howard Taft.
events.html: • 1912 – Woodrow Wilson is elected the 28th President of the United States, defeating incumbent William Howard Taft.

events.description: King Otto of Bavaria is deposed by his cousin, Prince Regent Ludwig, who assumes the title Ludwig III.
events.html: • 1913 – King Otto of Bavaria is deposed by his cousin, Prince Regent Ludwig, who assumes the title Ludwig III.

events.description: World War I: France and the British Empire declare war on the Ottoman Empire.
events.html: • 1914 – World War I: France and the British Empire declare war on the Ottoman Empire.

events.description: The Kingdom of Poland is proclaimed by the Act of 5th November of the emperors of Germany and Austria-Hungary.
events.html: • 1916 – The Kingdom of Poland is proclaimed by the Act of 5th November of the emperors of Germany and Austria-Hungary.

events.description: The Everett massacre takes place in Everett, Washington as political differences lead to a shoot-out between the Industrial Workers of the World organizers and local police.
events.html: • 1916 – The Everett massacre takes place in Everett, Washington as political differences lead to a shoot-out between the Industrial Workers of the World organizers and local police.

events.description: Lenin calls for the October Revolution.
events.html: • 1917 – Lenin calls for the October Revolution.

events.description: Tikhon is elected the Patriarch of Moscow and of the Russian Orthodox Church.
events.html: • 1917 – Tikhon is elected the Patriarch of Moscow and of the Russian Orthodox Church.

events.description: Secret agent Sidney Reilly, the first "super-spy" of the 20th century, is executed by the OGPU, the secret police of the Soviet Union.
events.html: • 1925 – Secret agent Sidney Reilly, the first "super-spy" of the 20th century, is executed by the OGPU, the secret police of the Soviet Union.

events.description: World War II: The British armed merchant cruiser HMS Jervis Bay is sunk by the German pocket battleship Admiral Scheer.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: The British armed merchant cruiser HMS Jervis Bay is sunk by the German pocket battleship Admiral Scheer.

events.description: Franklin D. Roosevelt is the first and only President of the United States to be elected to a third term.
events.html: • 1940 – Franklin D. Roosevelt is the first and only President of the United States to be elected to a third term.

events.description: World War II: Bombing of the Vatican.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: Bombing of the Vatican.

events.description: The three-day anti-Jewish riots in Tripolitania commence.
events.html: • 1945 – The three-day anti-Jewish riots in Tripolitania commence.[5]

events.description: Korean War: British and Australian forces from the 27th British Commonwealth Brigade successfully halted the advancing Chinese 117th Division during the Battle of Pakchon.
events.html: • 1950 – Korean War: British and Australian forces from the 27th British Commonwealth Brigade successfully halted the advancing Chinese 117th Division during the Battle of Pakchon.

events.description: After being destroyed in World War II, the rebuilt Vienna State Opera reopens with a performance of Beethoven's Fidelio.
events.html: • 1955 – After being destroyed in World War II, the rebuilt Vienna State Opera reopens with a performance of Beethoven's Fidelio.

events.description: Suez Crisis: British and French paratroopers land in Egypt after a week-long bombing campaign.
events.html: • 1956 – Suez Crisis: British and French paratroopers land in Egypt after a week-long bombing campaign.

events.description: Richard Nixon is elected as 37th President of the United States.
events.html: • 1968 – Richard Nixon is elected as 37th President of the United States.

events.description: The Military Assistance Command, Vietnam reports the lowest weekly American soldier death toll in five years (24).
events.html: • 1970 – The Military Assistance Command, Vietnam reports the lowest weekly American soldier death toll in five years (24).

events.description: The Byford Dolphin diving bell accident kills five and leaves one severely injured.
events.html: • 1983 – The Byford Dolphin diving bell accident kills five and leaves one severely injured.

events.description: USS Rentz, USS Reeves and USS Oldendorf visit Qingdao, China; the first US naval visit to China since 1949.
events.html: • 1986 – USS Rentz, USS Reeves and USS Oldendorf visit Qingdao, China; the first US naval visit to China since 1949.

events.description: Rabbi Meir Kahane, founder of the far-right Kach movement, is shot dead after a speech at a New York City hotel.
events.html: • 1990 – Rabbi Meir Kahane, founder of the far-right Kach movement, is shot dead after a speech at a New York City hotel.

events.description: Saddam Hussein, the former president of Iraq, and his co-defendants Barzan Ibrahim al-Tikriti and Awad Hamed al-Bandar, are sentenced to death in the al-Dujail trial for their roles in the 1982 massacre of 148 Shia Muslims.
